ed -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe lifecourse perspective continues to be an important subject in the social sciences. Researching the Lifecourse offers a distinctive approach in that it truly covers the lifecourse (childhood, adulthood and older age), focusing on innovative methods and case study examples from a variety of European and North American contexts. This original approach connects theory and practice from across the social sciences by situating methodology and research design within relevant conceptual frameworks. This diverse collection features methods that are linked to questions of time, space and mobilities while providing practitioners with practical detail in each chapter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocial sciencesxResearch. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aAkesson, Bree, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBianco, Ann Del, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlaakilde, Anne Leonora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowlby, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDureau, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Rosalind, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalola, Bisola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiroud, Matthieu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodwin, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardill, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardill, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aImbert, Christophe,